## Transaction Boundaries

### Write Operations

Each use case that mutates state runs in one transaction:

1. Validate invariants
2. Lock or version-check contested rows
3. Persist changes
4. Emit domain events (outbox in same transaction when using event-driven patterns)

### Cross-Aggregate Consistency

Prefer eventual consistency via domain events for cross-context updates.

Use synchronous cross-table updates within one transaction only when:

- Financial correctness requires it (inventory reservation + order line creation)
- The operation is short and well-bounded

### Saga / Compensation

Long-running flows (checkout ‚Üí payment ‚Üí fulfillment) use:

- Idempotency keys on external calls
- Explicit state machines on aggregates
- Compensation or retry-safe handlers on failure

---

## Security

- Application connects with least-privilege DB role (no superuser in app)
- Separate roles for migrations (DDL) and runtime (DML)
- Never embed credentials in code; use environment variables or secrets manager
- Enable SSL for all non-local connections
- Row-level security (RLS) for multi-tenant deployments when required

See `security/03-data-protection` for PII handling.

---

## Backup and Recovery

- Continuous WAL archiving or managed-service PITR
- Daily logical backups for development restore testing
- Test restore procedure quarterly
- Document RPO/RTO targets per environment

Production schema changes always go through Alembic migrations (`database/02-migrations`).

---

## Observability

Log and monitor:

- Slow queries (> 500ms warn, > 2s alert)
- Connection pool exhaustion
- Deadlock occurrences
- Migration execution time
- Replication lag (if replicas)

Use `EXPLAIN (ANALYZE, BUFFERS)` in staging before shipping query changes.

---

## Environment Standards

| Environment | Purpose | Data |
|-------------|---------|------|
| local | Developer machines | Seed data, anonymized fixtures |
| staging | Pre-production validation | Anonymized production subset or synthetic |
| production | Live traffic | Real customer data ‚Äî strict access controls |

Never copy production data with real PII to local machines without anonymization.

---

## Anti-Patterns

- Storing prices or inventory only in Redis without PostgreSQL backing
- Using `SELECT *` in production repository code
- N+1 queries without eager loading strategy
- Missing indexes on foreign key columns
- Float types for money or inventory quantities
- Manual DDL in production outside Alembic
- Long-running transactions during Stripe webhook processing

